MedwithMoni EDA

The goal of this project is to perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) to uncover key insights from scraped Instagram data of medical vloggers and influencers. I aim to identify trends, peak post times, and audience engagement through metrics such as likes, comments, hashtag usage, and video performance. The main priority is to determine the optimal times and frequency for posting.

In[10]:
# Ensure datetime is in correct format (handle 12-hour format with AM/PM)
df["upload_time"] = pd.to_datetime(df["upload_time"], format="%I:%M %p")

# Extract hour for grouping
df["upload_hour"] = df["upload_time"].dt.hour

# Define correct order of days
day_order = ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"]

# Convert 'day_of_week' to categorical type with the correct order
df["day_of_week"] = pd.Categorical(df["day_of_week"], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

# Group by day of the week and hour of upload
upload_heatmap_data = (
    df.groupby(["day_of_week", "upload_hour"], observed=False).size().reset_index(name="upload_count")
)

# Pivot the data for the heatmap
heatmap_pivot = upload_heatmap_data.pivot(
    index="upload_hour", columns="day_of_week", values="upload_count"
)

# Fill NaN values with 0 and convert to integer type
heatmap_pivot = heatmap_pivot.fillna(0).astype(int)

# Plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_pivot, cmap="YlGnBu", annot=True, fmt="d", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Collective Upload Timing Heatmap")
plt.xlabel("Day of the Week")
plt.ylabel("Hour of the Day (UTC)")
plt.show()

# Ensure datetime_pst is in datetime format
df["datetime_pst"] = pd.to_datetime(df["datetime_pst"])

# Extract hour and date from PST timestamp
df["upload_hour_pst"] = df["datetime_pst"].dt.hour
df["date_pst"] = df["datetime_pst"].dt.date
df["day_of_week_pst"] = df["datetime_pst"].dt.day_name()

# Define correct order of days
day_order = ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"]

# Convert 'day_of_week_pst' to categorical type with the correct order
df["day_of_week_pst"] = pd.Categorical(df["day_of_week_pst"], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

# Group by PST day of the week and upload hour
upload_heatmap_data = (
    df.groupby(["day_of_week_pst", "upload_hour_pst"], observed=False).size().reset_index(name="upload_count")
)

    index="upload_hour_pst", columns="day_of_week_pst", values="upload_count"
)

Note

Given some more context behind uploads, most uploads are done on wednesday and thursday, followed by monday. Other days are are not too far behind with the minimum upload being 92 on Saturdays. Looking at standard deviation, Monday has the largest spread while Wednesday has the lowest spread. Considerations to look at Wednesday as the core. Since uploads seems to visibily be around the same range, Wednesday can be a good indicator of when to best upload. Variations on times between Wednesday and Thursday is upload time. # Extract hour and date from PST timestamp

df["date_pst"] = df["datetime_pst"].dt.date
df["day_of_week_pst"] = df["datetime_pst"].dt.day_name()

# Define correct order of days
day_order = ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"]

# Convert 'day_of_week_pst' to categorical type with the correct order
df["day_of_week_pst"] = pd.Categorical(df["day_of_week_pst"], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

# Group by PST day of the week and upload hour
upload_heatmap_data = (
    df.groupby(["day_of_week_pst", "upload_hour_pst"], observed=False).size().reset_index(name="upload_count")
)

# Pivot the data for the heatmap
heatmap_pivot = upload_heatmap_data.pivot(
    index="upload_hour_pst", columns="day_of_week_pst", values="upload_count"
)

# Fill NaN values with 0 and convert to integer type
heatmap_pivot = heatmap_pivot.fillna(0).astype(int)

# Add a 'Total' column summing uploads across all days for each hour
heatmap_pivot["Total"] = heatmap_pivot.sum(axis=1)

# Reorder columns to place 'Total' at the end
heatmap_pivot = heatmap_pivot[list(day_order) + ["Total"]]

# Plot the heatmap with the total column
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_pivot, cmap="YlGnBu", annot=True, fmt="d", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Collective Upload Timing Heatmap (PST)")
plt.xlabel("Day of the Week (PST)")
plt.ylabel("Hour of the Day (PST)")

Note

The more popular the channel gets, the more they upload which makes perfect sense. Averages being:

  1. Small 2k-10k
  • 6 days average, hovering 5-7 days
  1. Growing 10k - 50k
  • 3-4 days average, hovering 1-6 days
  1. Established 50k - 100k
  • 2 days average, hovering 1-2 days
  1. Popular 100k - 250k
  • 1 day average hovering 0-1 days

Though there are a frew outliers here and there for the established and popular creators, they seem to uploaded more frequently. So given this, it make sense that big creators upload more freqently. Looking at current goals of the user, looking at growing is the best bet as they are a much smaller channel but a growing one. given that 3-4 days and no more than 6 would be an optimal route for them to upload.

# Function to get top 5 hashtags for each category
def top_hashtags_by_category(df, category_column, hashtag_column):
    top_hashtags = {}
    
    for category in df[category_column].unique():
        # Filter hashtags for the category
        category_hashtags = df[df[category_column] == category][hashtag_column].str.split().explode().dropna()
        
        # Count the occurrences of each hashtag
        hashtag_counts = Counter(category_hashtags)
        
        # Get the top 10 most common hashtags for category
        top_category_hashtags = hashtag_counts.most_common(5)
        
        # Store the results in the dictionary
        top_hashtags[category] = top_category_hashtags
    
    return top_hashtags

# Create function to get top 5 hashtags by each category order by count
def top_hashtags_by_category(df, category_column, hashtag_column):
    top_hashtags = {}
    
    # Category range
    category_order = ['Low (0-10K)', 'Medium (10K-50K)', 'High (50K-200K)', 'Very High (200K-500K)', 'Viral (500K+)']
    
    # Sort by category order
    for category in category_order:
        # Filter hashtags for the category
        category_hashtags = df[df[category_column] == category][hashtag_column].str.split().explode().dropna()
        
        # Count the occurrences of each hashtag
        hashtag_counts = Counter(category_hashtags)
        
        # Get the top 5 most common hashtags for this category
        top_category_hashtags = sorted(hashtag_counts.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:5]
        
        # Store results into dictionary
        top_hashtags[category] = top_category_hashtags
    
    return top_hashtags
